  "prompt": "Does a senator get security protection?",
  "response": "In the United States, senators generally do not receive permanent security protection comparable to that provided for the President or Vice President. Security measures for senators typically depend on the specific situation and any perceived threats. \n\nThe U.S. Capitol Police are responsible for the security of members of Congress, including senators, and provide protection while they are in the Capitol Complex. If a senator faces specific threats or if there's a heightened risk, additional security measures can be deployed, which might include personal security details or enhanced protections at their homes. \n\nFor senators holding leadership positions, such as the Senate Majority or Minority Leader, enhanced security measures are often provided due to their higher public profile.",
